"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89830","Department for Transport","false","2014-09-05","<p> </p><p>Shipping companies are required to have in place procedures for ensuring that the weighed weights of trucks are used for stability calculations, and these procedures are documented in the ships Safety Management System which is audited regularly by surveyors of the Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA). MCA surveyors inspect car ferries in operation, and part of the checks confirm that the ships' masters are correctly using the weight information supplied by weighbridges.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>As a result of these proactive audit process the MCA does not routinely collect information on compliance with the Merchant Shipping (Weighing of Goods Vehicles and other Cargo) Regulations 1988 (as amended).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2014-09-05T12:01:35.7055576Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89830/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89830/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-08-29","Ferries: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the current level of compliance is with the (a) Merchant Shipping (Weighing of Goods Vehicles and other Cargo) Regulations 1988, (b) Merchant Shipping (Weighing of Goods Vehicles and other Cargo) (Amendment) Regulations 1989 and (c) Merchant Shipping (Weighing of Goods Vehicles and other Cargo) (Application to non-UK Ships) Regulations 1989 at each UK port licensed to operate passenger ferry services.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89831","Department for Transport","false","2014-09-05","<p> </p><p>The Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency’s (DVLA) targets for processing driving licence applications are to deliver:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>- 98% of first provisional driving licences within eight working days;</p><p> </p><p>- 98% of vocational driving licences within eight working days; and</p><p> </p><p>- 98% of all other driving licence applications, including renewal applications within 10 working days</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p><p>Where a driving licence application requires medical investigations, the target is to conclude 90% of all cases and make a licensing decision within 90 working days</p></td></tr><tr><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td></tr><tr><td> </td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2014-09-05T12:10:28.6194175Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89831/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/89831/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2014-08-29","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the current target timeframe is for processing of driving licence (a) applications and (b) renewals; and whether the same timeframe applies in the case of licences that have a medical test as part of the application.","false","Biography information for Katy Clark","North Ayrshire and Arran","Katy Clark","207185"
